{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17492538","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17492538"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":0,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:21+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T06:35:21+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1094"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"1094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/1094"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.08,0.05,0.06,0.58,0.24]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1094"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90284"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"1094","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/1094"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1094"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74537"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"3"},{"type":"tags","id":"64"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"4955"},{"type":"tags","id":"4987"},{"type":"tags","id":"4988"},{"type":"tags","id":"11629"},{"type":"tags","id":"11640"},{"type":"tags","id":"11650"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"2363"},{"type":"contributions","id":"30956"},{"type":"contributions","id":"34940"},{"type":"contributions","id":"42217"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90284","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/90284"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 36-year-old woman presents with an area of hyperpigmentation on her lower abdomen. She thinks the area of concern has developed over the last several weeks; initially starting as a faint red net-like pattern, then becoming darker in colour. She also complains of associated itch in the same area. She has been applying a bland emollient to help soothe the itch.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHer medical history includes hypothyroidism and endometriosis. She takes the oral contraceptive pill daily, and paracetamol and ibuprofen as needed. She also uses hot water bottles as non-pharmacological analgesia.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EShe denies any recent infections. She reports she has been systemically well recently, however does have chronic abdominal pain secondary to endometriosis. She denies any dysuria or change in bowel habits.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOn examination she has a livedo or reticular pattern of non-blanching erythema and hyperpigmentation across her right lower abdomen (Image). There is no scale present. Her abdomen is soft, with mild tenderness in all abdominal quadrants.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following is the most likely diagnosis?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Erythema induratum","Erythema annulare centrifugum","Erythema marginatum","Erythema ab igne","Livedo reticularis"],"correctOptions":[3],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ERepeated use of hot water bottles is the key part to the patient\u0027s history. The clinical picture is consistent with \u003Cstrong\u003Eerythema ab igne\u003C/strong\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema ab igne is a cutaneous reaction to repeated exposure of direct heat or infrared radiation to a person\u2019s skin.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeat sources that can cause this condition if there is repeated exposure include:\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cul\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHot water bottles, heating blankets or heat pads to treat chronic pain\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EHeated car seats, space heaters or fireplaces\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003EOccupational hazards of silversmiths and jewellers (face exposed), bakers and chefs (arms, face exposed)\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003Cli\u003E\u003Cp\u003ELaptop computers rested on the anterior thighs\u003C/p\u003E\u003C/li\u003E\u003C/ul\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema ab igne has been reported in people with chronic pancreatitis, and is associated with hypothyroidism and lymphoedema.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAn important clinical differential for erythema ab igne is livedo reticularis. In livedo reticularis however, the skin changes are symmetrical (not focal to the point of heat source) and telangiectatic (rather than pigmented).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EPrimary treatment of erythema ag igne is the removal of the causative heat source. Investigation of underlying causes of pain and excluding hypothyroidism should be considered.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EMild cases will settle spontaneously. In severe cases, abnormal pigmentation, atrophy or scarring may persist. Rarely, these lesions may develop into cutaneous malignancy. If there is any clinical suspicion of epidermal atypia, regular skin examination \u00b1 biopsies are recommended.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema induratum (Bazin disease) is a panniculitis that typically presents on the calves, associated with a \u003Cem\u003EMycobacterium tuberculosis\u003C/em\u003E infection.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema annulare centrifugum is thought to be a chronic hypersensitivity reaction characterised by annular erythematous lesions, with a pathognomonic delicate scale behind the advancing edge (\u2018trailing scale\u2019).\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EErythema marginatum is a non-pruritic macular annular rash that typically occurs on the limbs which is associated with acute rheumatic fever.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Erythema ab igne is a cutaneous reaction to chronic direct heat exposure"],"references":["Kettelhut EA, Traylor J, Roach JP. Erythema Ab Igne. [Updated 2020 Aug 10]. In: StatPearls [Internet]. Treasure Island (FL): StatPearls Publishing; 2021 Jan-. Available from: https://www.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/books/NBK538250/"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74537"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"1094"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[{"type":"media","id":"18464"}]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"media","id":"18464","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/media/18464"},"attributes":{"mimeType":"image/jpeg","url":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/630c4fc2-5b78-41cc-a89d-b1eb00ec030a.jpg","thumbUrl":"https://app.emedici.com/storage/media/630c4fc2-5b78-41cc-a89d-b1eb00ec030a.jpg","isProcessed":true,"width":587,"height":440}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"74537","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/74537"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2025-03-13T16:11:19+10:30","updatedAt":"2025-07-05T12:40:43+09:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"1094"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"90284"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"3","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/3"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\uddf4","name":"Dermatology","synonyms":[],"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":"2024-11-21T09:49:42+10:30"},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"1"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"64","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/64"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Diagnosis","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"5"}},"heading":{"data":null}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"72","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/72"},"attributes":{"emoji":"","name":"Graduating","synonyms":null,"description":"Only suitable for a graduating medical student at the end of their degree","position":1,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"6"}},"head